arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
Fill below Locus 51 in the pool

Locus 52 is the soil below Locus 51 under the floor (Locus 49) of the ‘covered pool.’ The soil is a fine loose silt (Munsell 7.5 YR 2.5/2 very dark brown). Small amounts of bone, pottery, glass, metal, and small stones are included in the soil. Some architectural fragments are also present, including a column drum and a number of pieces of opus sectile. In addition to the many coins found in this locus (ten in total!), many olive pits were recovered. Christopher Tuttle has suggested that this would by typical in dumping layers when refuse is used – the olive pits suggest that the useless byproduct from the production of olive oil was perhaps being dumped into this pool. Ash is also in significant quantities in the locus, supporting this hypothesis. This soil locus, and those above and below it in the pool are the result of dumping, meant to fill in the pool after it went out of use. This is illustrated especially well in this locus, as it slopes from north to south, easily the result of the process of dumping. It is phased to Stage 4, with the covering of the pool and other post-363 alterations to the Complex.
Post-363 reworking of the Complex, including blockage of doorways and the covering of the ornamental pool.
3.10 m north south -by- 1.45 m east west (exposed).
